ODE XVI.

TO MAECENAS.

A 13th fonress, strongly barred With door and stanchion‚ and a guard Of waheful dogs, had long immured The virgin Danah, secured

From midnight wantons bold : But Jupiter and Venus laughed At old Acrisius’ futile craft3 For safe the path, and easy trod, That lay before th’ enamoured God

· Converted into gold.

That gold! that gold! which loveth well To pass by gate and sentinel! And keener than the lightning's shock To penetrate the guarded roch3

The Argive augur lost

His home and life from lucre’s thirst3 By brihes the Macedonian burst Through forts, and rival kings o'erthrew3 And bribes ensnared the venal crew

Of Pompey’s naval host.
